WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.160
So we're going to talk very briefly about logging and analysis right now, and then we'll

00:05.160 --> 00:08.480
get into a little more deeply when we talk about security information and event management

00:08.480 --> 00:10.400
systems in domain 7.

00:10.400 --> 00:13.600
But let's start with the basics.

00:13.600 --> 00:15.480
Why do we logging and monitoring?

00:15.480 --> 00:16.480
I like this slide.

00:16.480 --> 00:18.760
It does a good job of summarizing why we do this.

00:18.760 --> 00:22.600
First of all, we only want to log what is relevant.

00:22.600 --> 00:26.840
It is absolutely possible with our systems to produce, especially modern systems, to produce

00:26.840 --> 00:29.960
an unbelievable amount of logging data.

00:29.960 --> 00:31.440
But we don't care about all of that.

00:31.440 --> 00:34.400
You only want to log what is relevant.

00:34.400 --> 00:36.400
How do you determine how to log what is relevant?

00:36.400 --> 00:40.280
A really good way of doing this is to go back to risk management.

00:40.280 --> 00:44.160
If you think about what are the key risks for an asset, that's a pretty good way of thinking

00:44.160 --> 00:47.760
about how would we detect if one of those risks had occurred?

00:47.760 --> 00:49.440
Maybe that's what we should turn logging on for.

00:49.440 --> 00:51.720
So only log what is relevant.

00:51.720 --> 00:54.520
And then review those logs.

00:54.520 --> 00:58.760
Someone has to be proactively or some system has to be proactively looking at those logs.

00:58.760 --> 01:00.800
And this is where you truly do new system.

01:00.800 --> 01:03.520
Modern day systems can produce just, especially in a big environment.

01:03.520 --> 01:05.760
You can have millions of events happening per second.

01:05.760 --> 01:08.480
And there's no way that a person could actually look through that.

01:08.480 --> 01:14.240
You need a system involved that's able to look at all this event data and be able to identify

01:14.240 --> 01:15.680
useful information.

01:15.680 --> 01:18.920
And you really do want to be reviewing the logs proactively.

01:18.920 --> 01:22.440
You can just go back and look at the logs after you've had a breach, but it's better to

01:22.440 --> 01:23.920
do it proactively.

01:23.920 --> 01:25.760
And then the final thing, what are you actually looking for?

01:25.760 --> 01:28.840
Well, you're looking for things like errors and anomalies.

01:28.840 --> 01:30.480
And here's a good summary, right?

01:30.480 --> 01:35.040
Errors, unexpected errors, are a good indication that a system might not be working properly.

01:35.040 --> 01:37.800
Modification to a system, especially if it's unauthorized modification.

01:37.800 --> 01:41.880
That's probably something you want to look at and breaches.

01:41.880 --> 01:46.080
Now as I mentioned in domain seven, we'll go into seam, sim systems, and much more detail.

01:46.080 --> 01:51.800
And we'll talk through all the steps that they go through for the aggregation generation,

01:51.800 --> 01:52.800
correlation of logs.

01:52.800 --> 01:55.640
We'll talk about that later on.

01:55.640 --> 02:00.720
For now, let's just say that when it comes to where can we collect a log event data from

02:00.720 --> 02:01.720
everywhere?

02:01.720 --> 02:02.720
And what do we want to do?

02:02.720 --> 02:07.040
We want to pull all that data into our log correlation system into one central system so

02:07.040 --> 02:14.560
that we can then analyze that data, look for the proverbial needle and a stack of needles.

02:14.560 --> 02:20.360
One of the problems we face when logging is our endpoint devices, things like our firewalls,

02:20.360 --> 02:23.000
can produce an enormous amount of logging data.

02:23.000 --> 02:26.040
But they typically have very limited storage on board.

02:26.040 --> 02:31.120
And so if we have a requirement to keep a huge amount of logging data, it's often difficult

02:31.120 --> 02:33.480
or impossible to do that on the endpoint.

02:33.480 --> 02:37.720
So let's talk about a couple of methods of how we can limit log file sizes.

02:37.720 --> 02:42.080
Two major methods that you need to know about, circular overwrite and clipping levels.

02:42.080 --> 02:44.800
Now let's start with circular overwrite.

02:44.800 --> 02:50.160
The way circular overwrite works is you set a maximum log file size or length.

02:50.160 --> 02:56.200
And then you start writing log event data until you reach the maximum file size or the

02:56.200 --> 03:01.120
maximum number of lines and then you circle back to the top and start overwriting.

03:01.120 --> 03:03.520
That's circular overwrite.

03:03.520 --> 03:07.160
And what it means is that your log file size is never ending at larger than the maximum

03:07.160 --> 03:11.880
number of entries or the file size that you set because as soon as you reach that maximum,

03:11.880 --> 03:15.200
you circle back to the top and start overwriting.

03:15.200 --> 03:19.080
The other method you can use is what's known as clipping levels.

03:19.080 --> 03:23.200
When clipping levels is this idea that we set a threshold below that threshold, don't

03:23.200 --> 03:24.720
bother logging anything.

03:24.720 --> 03:27.120
Above that threshold, start logging.

03:27.120 --> 03:29.880
Here's an example.

03:29.880 --> 03:32.560
Failed or incorrect passwords.

03:32.560 --> 03:37.200
So when I change my password for the first month or first week anyways, I type in the

03:37.200 --> 03:40.240
wrong password and it's a failed log event.

03:40.240 --> 03:42.480
This happens all the time for people.

03:42.480 --> 03:47.440
And so the vast majority of the time, if you see one failed log in attempt, it's not concerning.

03:47.440 --> 03:50.960
So you might set a threshold and you would say, you know what, below say three failed log

03:50.960 --> 03:54.320
in attempts in 30 seconds or not going to log anything.

03:54.320 --> 03:58.440
So all those times that people are just fat fingering their password or forgetting their

03:58.440 --> 04:00.960
password, you're not logging any of that.

04:00.960 --> 04:05.320
But if you suddenly see like 50 failed log in attempts within 30 seconds, should you be

04:05.320 --> 04:06.320
logging that?

04:06.320 --> 04:07.320
Absolutely.

04:07.320 --> 04:10.200
That's probably someone trying to brute force your system.

04:10.200 --> 04:11.760
And so that's the idea of clipping levels.

04:11.760 --> 04:15.240
You set a threshold below that threshold, don't log anything.

04:15.240 --> 04:18.360
Love that threshold, start logging.

04:18.360 --> 04:20.320
Here's a good question.

04:20.320 --> 04:25.480
Which of these methods, circular overwrite or clipping levels, would be better if you

04:25.480 --> 04:29.480
wanted to detect a breach?

04:29.480 --> 04:31.320
And the answer is clipping levels.

04:31.320 --> 04:34.880
And the reason is that with circular overwrite, if you want to investigate a breach, you need

04:34.880 --> 04:35.880
the log data.

04:35.880 --> 04:40.400
And in circular overwrite, you're erasing your log data, data, you're overwriting your

04:40.400 --> 04:42.280
data once you get to a certain point.

04:42.280 --> 04:45.840
Whereas with clipping levels, you're limiting the amount of data, but you're not ever

04:45.840 --> 04:46.840
overwriting it.

04:46.840 --> 04:50.640
So if you get a question like that, the better type of logging, of a better method of

04:50.640 --> 04:56.280
limiting log file sizes, if you're looking for a breach, is clipping levels.

04:56.280 --> 04:59.320
Final part about logging here that I want to mention.

04:59.320 --> 05:03.520
And this relates to the time that we attach to a log file.

05:03.520 --> 05:05.320
You want to have consistent timestamps.

05:05.320 --> 05:09.960
I'm going to talk later on in the SIM system about how if you want to correlate events,

05:09.960 --> 05:11.200
line them up with each other.

05:11.200 --> 05:13.400
You need to have consistent timestamps.

05:13.400 --> 05:18.140
Has to be the same date, you know, same year, month, day, format, same, 12 or 25 hour

05:18.140 --> 05:21.440
clock format, whatever it is, make it consistent.

05:21.440 --> 05:26.240
The final piece is all of the systems in your environment need to have the same system

05:26.240 --> 05:27.240
time.

05:27.240 --> 05:31.200
If you want to be able to trace, track, how in a tracker, how an attacker traversed your

05:31.200 --> 05:35.320
network, got into different systems, got a foothold here and then moved there, it is

05:35.320 --> 05:41.440
very difficult to trace and figure out exactly what someone did, an attacker did, if your

05:41.440 --> 05:45.720
systems have different clock times, if this one's five seconds faster, that one's three

05:45.720 --> 05:49.400
seconds slower, it becomes very difficult to trace events.

05:49.400 --> 05:54.240
And so the way that we can make sure that all of our systems, clocks are aligned is through

05:54.240 --> 05:58.640
the MNTP protocol, network time protocol.

05:58.640 --> 06:04.240
And as the name implies, this protocol allows a server to synchronize its system clock.

06:04.240 --> 06:08.520
And there are basically what you can connect with this is an atomic clock.

06:08.520 --> 06:12.080
And through the MNTP protocol, you can synchronize your system clock with one of these world

06:12.080 --> 06:16.400
atomic clocks through NASA or other US agencies and other agencies around the world.

06:16.400 --> 06:20.300
And if every system in your environment is using the MNTP to synchronize the system

06:20.300 --> 06:24.440
clock, all the servers in the environment, all the systems in the environment will have

06:24.440 --> 06:25.440
the exact same time.

